    <Folder>
      <name>Day 7: Northeast Wonders - July 20</name>
      <description>A journey from eastern Iceland toward the north, with stops at some of Iceland's most impressive geological wonders. From dramatic sea cliffs to Europe's most powerful waterfall and an otherworldly canyon, this day showcases the raw force of nature that shaped Iceland's remarkable landscape.</description>
      
      <!-- Starting point -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Ásgeirsstaðir Cottages (Starting Point)</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>Morning Departure</h3>
            <p>Starting point for Day 7, leaving from these cozy cabins in a serene rural setting. Ásgeirsstaðir Cottages offer private cabins in a peaceful location, providing excellent opportunities to enjoy Iceland's midnight sun and potentially spot wildlife in the surrounding countryside.</p>
            <p><strong>Accommodation details:</strong><br>
            Price: $246.00 per night<br>
            Standard Cabin, 1 Bedroom<br>
            Confirmation: 73055400652002<br>
            Phone: +354 8686352</p>
            <p><strong>Tip:</strong> Have breakfast at the cottages before departing early to accommodate this long driving day.</p>
            <br>
            <img src="https://dynamic-media-cdn.tripadvisor.com/media/photo-o/0a/81/3c/ef/asgeirsstathir-cottages.jpg?w=1200&h=-1&s=1" width="300">
          ]]>
        </description>
        <styleUrl>#accommodation</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>-14.5142,65.4047,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>

      <!-- Hidden Gem -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Þerribjörg Sea Cliffs (Ker Cliffs)</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>Morning Activity - Hidden Gem</h3>
            <p>One of the most breathtaking beaches and coastlines in East Iceland. These dramatic cliffs offer stunning views of the ocean and rugged coastline.</p>
            <p><strong>Location details:</strong><br>
            Access via gravel road 917 (Hlíðarvegur)<br>
            Any car May-October<br>
            Easy 1.5-hour family hike<br>
            Scenic mountain pass</p>
            <p><strong>Tip:</strong> This is a perfect morning activity while heading north. The area is relatively unknown to tourists, making it a peaceful stop with incredible views.</p>
            <br>
            <img src="https://epiciceland.net/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/Therribjorg-Sea-Cliffs-%E2%80%93-Ker-Cliffs-and-Veithileysufjorthur-fjord-East-Iceland-1-900x500.jpg" width="300">
          ]]>
        </description>
        <styleUrl>#hiddenGem</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>-13.7761,65.5224,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>

      <!-- UNESCO Site -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Vatnajökull National Park</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>UNESCO World Heritage Site</h3>
            <p>Encompassing nearly 14% of Iceland, this is Europe's largest national park, protecting diverse landscapes from glaciers to geothermal areas. The park contains Europe's largest glacier (Vatnajökull), active volcanoes, massive waterfalls, and vast wilderness areas.</p>
            <p><strong>Notable features:</strong><br>
            - The varied geology creates habitats for unique plant and animal communities<br>
            - The UNESCO designation recognizes the park's outstanding example of geological processes and features<br>
            - Part of the park will be visible throughout much of the day's journey</p>
            <p><strong>Tip:</strong> Keep your camera ready as you drive through sections of the park - the landscapes change dramatically and provide numerous photo opportunities.</p>
            <br>
            <img src="https://cdn.britannica.com/15/164215-050-78647512/Vatnajokull-Iceland.jpg" width="300">
          ]]>
        </description>
        <styleUrl>#unesco</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>-16.9814,64.4153,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>

      <!-- Main Attraction -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Dettifoss Waterfall</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>Morning - Europe's Most Powerful Waterfall</h3>
            <p>Europe's most powerful waterfall, an awe-inspiring display of nature's raw power. The massive cascade drops 150 feet and spans 330 feet across, creating a thundering roar that can be heard from a considerable distance.</p>
            <p><strong>Location details:</strong><br>
            - 330 ft wide, 150 ft high<br>
            - Page 225 in Moon guidebook<br>
            - Accessible via Route 862 (paved) on west side or Route 864 (gravel) on east side<br>
            - 30-minute walk from parking area</p>
            <p><strong>Tip:</strong> The western side of Dettifoss (Route 862) is recommended for your rental car as it's fully paved. The eastern approach (Route 864) is rougher but offers views of additional waterfalls like Selfoss.</p>
            <br>
            <img src="https://guidetoiceland.imgix.net/373228/x/0/dettifoss-is-the-most-powerful-waterfall-in-europe-1.jpg" width="300">
          ]]>
        </description>
        <styleUrl>#mainAttraction</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>-16.3843,65.8149,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>

      <!-- Main Attraction -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Ásbyrgi Canyon</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>Afternoon - Mythological Horse-Shaped Canyon</h3>
            <p>This remarkable horseshoe-shaped canyon features sheer cliff walls rising up to 100 meters, encircling a lush, wooded plain. According to Norse mythology, it was formed when Odin's eight-legged horse Sleipnir touched one of its hooves to the ground.</p>
            <p><strong>Location details:</strong><br>
            - Page 224 in Moon guidebook<br>
            - Several excellent short hiking options around the canyon floor<br>
            - Rich in birdlife and unique flora<br>
            - Part of the Diamond Circle tourist route</p>
            <p><strong>Tip:</strong> A short 1km hike leads to "Botnstjörn," a small pond at the canyon's innermost end. The central "island" of the horseshoe can be climbed via a marked path for panoramic views.</p>
            <br>
            <img src="https://guidetoiceland.imgix.net/349795/x/0/asbyrgi-canyon-is-actually-part-of-jokulsargljufur-canyon-1.jpg" width="300">
          ]]>
        </description>
        <styleUrl>#mainAttraction</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>-16.5076,66.0156,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>

      <!-- Alternative Activity -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Mývatn Nature Baths</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>Afternoon - Alternative Activity</h3>
            <p>A relaxing geothermal lagoon often described as the "Blue Lagoon of the North," but less crowded and more affordable. These mineral-rich azure waters offer a perfect way to rejuvenate during your journey.</p>
            <p><strong>Location details:</strong><br>
            - Entrance fee: $41<br>
            - Allow 2 hours for the full experience<br>
            - Less crowded alternative to Blue Lagoon<br>
            - Beautiful views of Lake Mývatn and surrounding volcanic landscape</p>
            <p><strong>Tip:</strong> This is an optional stop if time permits and you're interested in a relaxing break. Since you've already experienced the Blue Lagoon and Reykjadalur hot river, you might choose to skip this if time is tight.</p>
            <br>
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/69/M%C3%BDvatn_Nature_Baths.jpg" width="300">
          ]]>
        </description>
        <styleUrl>#alternative</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>-16.9095,65.6355,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>

      <!-- Featured Attraction -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Goðafoss Waterfall</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>Afternoon - "Waterfall of the Gods"</h3>
            <p>This horseshoe-shaped waterfall is not only spectacular but historically significant. The name comes from the year 1000 when Iceland converted to Christianity and the chieftain Þorgeir threw his pagan idols into the falls.</p>
            <p><strong>Location details:</strong><br>
            - Semicircular cascade about 100 feet wide and 40 feet high<br>
            - Powerful display of frothing white water against black basalt<br>
            - Easily accessible directly from Ring Road with parking on both sides<br>
            - Different viewing platforms offer varied perspectives</p>
            <p><strong>Tip:</strong> The midnight sun creates magical lighting conditions in summer evenings, making this a potential stop on the return if you have extra time.</p>
            <br>
            <img src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/54cd2f2ae4b011bba705a26a/1569430283187-6MZC3YGLJNXX4WRDPXX8/godafoss-waterfall-iceland" width="300">
          ]]>
        </description>
        <styleUrl>#featured</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>-17.5505,65.6830,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>

      <!-- Final Destination -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Akureyri (Final Destination)</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>Evening - Iceland's Northern Capital</h3>
            <p>Iceland's "Capital of the North," a charming town with cultural offerings set against the backdrop of Iceland's longest fjord and surrounding mountains.</p>
            <p><strong>Accommodation details:</strong><br>
            Airbnb - Hildur<br>
            $452.00 per night<br>
            Entire home/apt<br>
            Confirmation: HM8YWHA8PD<br>
            Phone: +354 893 7979</p>
            <p><strong>Evening recommendations:</strong><br>
            - Relaxed exploring of downtown Akureyri<br>
            - Dinner options: Rub23 (innovative seafood and sushi), Strikið (fine dining with views over the fjord), or Bryggjan (casual restaurant with good local food)</p>
            <p><strong>Tip:</strong> Akureyri is known for its heart-shaped traffic lights! The red lights are in the shape of hearts, a small detail that adds to the town's charm.</p>
            <br>
            <img src="https://www.traveo.is/weassets/items/origin/10061-b2a9cd4dddab49da.jpg" width="300">
          ]]>
        </description>
        <styleUrl>#accommodation</styleUrl>
        <Point>
          <coordinates>-18.0999,65.6826,0</coordinates>
        </Point>
      </Placemark>

      <!-- Alternative Activities Folder -->
      <Folder>
        <name>Alternative Attractions</name>
        <description>Other interesting places to visit on Day 7 if time permits or you prefer to customize your itinerary.</description>

        <Placemark>
          <name>Askja Caldera Hike</name>
          <description>
            <![CDATA[
              <h3>Alternative Activity - Requires F-Road Access</h3>
              <p>A dramatic volcanic crater with a milky blue lake nestled within the highlands of Iceland. This otherworldly landscape feels like visiting another planet.</p>
              <p><strong>Note:</strong> This requires significant detour on F-roads and is only advisable if you have experience with highland driving and ample time.</p>
              <br>
              <img src="https://guidetoiceland.imgix.net/316687/x/0/askja-is-a-caldera-in-the-heartland-of-iceland-surrounded-by-the-highlands-1.jpg" width="300">
            ]]>
          </description>
          <styleUrl>#alternative</styleUrl>
          <Point>
            <coordinates>-16.7500,65.0500,0</coordinates>
          </Point>
        </Placemark>
        
        <Placemark>
          <name>Grjótagjá Cave</name>
          <description>
            <![CDATA[
              <h3>Alternative Morning Activity</h3>
              <p>A small lava cave with a hot spring that was featured in Game of Thrones. While bathing is no longer permitted due to temperature fluctuations, it's still a fascinating geological site to visit.</p>
              <p><strong>Note:</strong> Located near Lake Mývatn, this could pair well with the Mývatn Nature Baths if choosing that option.</p>
              <br>
              <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5c/Grj%C3%B3tagj%C3%A1_Cave_Iceland_2013-03-20.jpg" width="300">
            ]]>
          </description>
          <styleUrl>#alternative</styleUrl>
          <Point>
            <coordinates>-16.8825,65.6263,0</coordinates>
          </Point>
        </Placemark>
        
        <Placemark>
          <name>Hverfjall Crater Hike</name>
          <description>
            <![CDATA[
              <h3>Alternative Morning Activity</h3>
              <p>A 2-mile loop hike around the rim of this nearly perfectly symmetrical tephra cone volcano. The crater is about 1km in diameter and 140m deep, formed in a volcanic eruption approximately 2,500 years ago.</p>
              <p><strong>Details:</strong> The hike takes about 1 hour and offers spectacular views of the surrounding Mývatn area. The black volcanic gravel path is well-marked but can be windy.</p>
              <br>
              <img src="https://photos.smugmug.com/Iceland/North-Iceland/i-mhLm2bF/1/L/hverfjall-crater-lake-myvatn-1-L.jpg" width="300">
            ]]>
          </description>
          <styleUrl>#alternative</styleUrl>
          <Point>
            <coordinates>-16.8748,65.6006,0</coordinates>
          </Point>
        </Placemark>
        
        <Placemark>
          <name>Bergárfoss Waterfall</name>
          <description>
            <![CDATA[
              <h3>Hidden Gem - Alternative Afternoon Stop</h3>
              <p>The prettiest and most secluded waterfall in North Iceland, rarely visited even by locals. This hidden gem requires some effort to reach but rewards visitors with a pristine, peaceful experience away from the crowds.</p>
              <p><strong>Access details:</strong> From Kolugljúfur Canyon, take gravel road south on eastern river bank for 4km, then walk. 4WD necessary year-round.</p>
              <br>
              <img src="https://epiciceland.net/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/Bergarfoss-1.jpg" width="300">
            ]]>
          </description>
          <styleUrl>#hiddenGem</styleUrl>
          <Point>
            <coordinates>-20.5000,65.3500,0</coordinates>
          </Point>
        </Placemark>
        
        <Placemark>
          <name>Krafla Volcano</name>
          <description>
            <![CDATA[
              <h3>Alternative Afternoon Activity</h3>
              <p>A 300-meter volcanic crater with an active geothermal area nearby. Krafla is one of Iceland's most active volcanic systems, with its last eruption period ending in 1984.</p>
              <p><strong>Highlights:</strong><br>
              - Víti Crater with its blue-green lake<br>
              - Leirhnjúkur geothermal area with steaming vents and colorful mud pots<br>
              - Krafla Power Station - one of Iceland's largest geothermal power plants</p>
              <br>
              <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/38/Lake_Viti_in_Krafla%2C_Iceland.JPG" width="300">
            ]]>
          </description>
          <styleUrl>#alternative</styleUrl>
          <Point>
            <coordinates>-16.7543,65.7176,0</coordinates>
          </Point>
        </Placemark>
        
        <Placemark>
          <name>Kverkfjöll</name>
          <description>
            <![CDATA[
              <h3>Hidden Gem - Major Detour</h3>
              <p>A glacial mountain range with ice caves, hot springs, and challenging hikes in the eastern highlands. This remote area offers some of Iceland's most striking contrasts where fire meets ice - hot springs emerging directly beneath glacial ice.</p>
              <p><strong>Access details:</strong> Via F902 (no river crossings) and/or F903 (two unbridged rivers). Requires guide or ranger consultation; summer only.</p>
              <p><strong>Note:</strong> This is a significant detour and would require substantial time commitment. Consider only if you are extending your trip.</p>
              <br>
              <img src="https://epiciceland.net/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/Kverkfjoll-Hot-Spring-10.jpg" width="300">
            ]]>
          </description>
          <styleUrl>#hiddenGem</styleUrl>
          <Point>
            <coordinates>-16.6000,64.7500,0</coordinates>
          </Point>
        </Placemark>
      </Folder>

      <!-- Driving Route -->
      <Placemark>
        <name>Day 7 Driving Route</name>
        <description>
          <![CDATA[
            <h3>Full Day Journey: 230 miles, 5.5 hours driving time</h3>
            <p>This is a significant driving day with numerous stops along the way. The route takes you from eastern Iceland toward the north, passing through diverse landscapes including mountains, lava fields, geothermal areas, and coastal scenery.</p>
            <p><strong>Key segments:</strong><br>
            - Ásgeirsstaðir to Þerribjörg Sea Cliffs: ~45 minutes<br>
            - Þerribjörg to Dettifoss: ~2.5 hours<br>
            - Dettifoss to Ásbyrgi Canyon: ~40 minutes<br>
            - Ásbyrgi to Goðafoss: ~1.5 hours<br>
            - Goðafoss to Akureyri: ~30 minutes</p>
            <p><strong>Important note:</strong> This is your longest driving day, so start early and prioritize which sites are most important to you. Consider skipping Mývatn Nature Baths if time is tight.</p>
          ]]>
        </description>
